The best approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides `IFileSystem` with mock support.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public bool OutputExists(string dir)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(dir);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// Pre-create directories as needed
mockFs.AddDirectory("/output");

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));
Assert.True(service.OutputExists("/output"));

service.Save("/data/new.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/new.txt"));
```

**Key points:**
- Replace `File.*` calls with `fileSystem.File.*` and `Directory.*` with `fileSystem.Directory.*`
- `MockFileSystem` is an in-memory filesystem — no disk I/O in tests
- Register as `AddSingleton` since `FileSystem` is stateless

